    </div>

    <div class="card">
      <h2>Comprehensive Guide</h2>
      <p>Saffron consists of the dried stigmas of the <em>Crocus sativus</em> flower. It must be hand-harvested, making it the most expensive spice by weight in the world.</p>
    <h3>Real vs Fake Saffron</h3>
    <p>Because of its price, saffron is frequently counterfeited. Real saffron threads are trumpet-shaped at one end. When placed in water, real saffron will slowly release a golden-yellow color and the thread will remain red. Fake saffron (often dyed corn silk) will bleed red instantly and the thread will turn white.</p>
    <h3>How to Bloom</h3>
    <p>Never throw dry saffron threads directly into a dish. To extract the maximum flavor and color, steep a pinch of slightly crushed saffron threads in 2-3 tablespoons of warm water, broth, or milk for 15-20 minutes before adding the liquid and threads to your recipe.</p>
    <h3>Cost-per-Dish Math</h3>
    <p>While expensive by weight ($10-$20 per gram), a single gram contains hundreds of threads. A typical recipe for four only requires a small pinch (about 10-20 threads), making the actual cost-per-dish only around $0.50 to $1.00.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="card">
      <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
      <h3>Why is saffron so expensive?</h3><p>It takes roughly 75,000 saffron blossoms to produce just one pound of saffron spice, and the delicate stigmas must be harvested entirely by hand.</p><h3>How do you properly bloom saffron?</h3><p>Crush a pinch of threads slightly, then steep them in warm water, broth, or milk for 15 to 20 minutes before using.</p><h3>What is a good substitute for saffron?</h3><p>For color, turmeric or annatto seeds work well. For flavor, there is no true substitute, though a tiny pinch of sweet paprika mixed with turmeric can hint at the earthiness.</p>
